# Fixing the Error with R6 Dynamically Created Methods

The error occurs because you're using two different mechanisms to define the same method:

1. In the parent class, you're dynamically creating a method named `foo` during initialization using `self[["foo"]] <- function() {...}`
2. In the child class, you're statically defining a method named `foo` in the class definition

When you create the child instance, R6 is trying to set up both versions of the method, and they conflict.

## Solution

You have two main options:

### Option 1: Consistently use static method definitions

```r
Parent <- R6::R6Class(
  "Parent",
  lock_objects = FALSE,
  public = list(
    foo = function() {
      print('foo')
    }
  )
)

Child <- R6::R6Class(
  "Child",
  inherit = Parent,
  lock_objects = FALSE,
  public = list(
    foo = function() {
      super$foo()
    }
  )
)

child <- Child$new()
child$foo()  # This will work
```

### Option 2: Consistently use dynamic method creation

```r
Parent <- R6::R6Class(
  "Parent",
  lock_objects = FALSE,
  public = list(
    initialize = function() {
      self[["foo"]] <- function() {
        print('foo')
      }
    }
  )
)

Child <- R6::R6Class(
  "Child",
  inherit = Parent,
  lock_objects = FALSE,
  public = list(
    initialize = function() {
      super$initialize()
      original_foo <- self[["foo"]]
      self[["foo"]] <- function() {
        original_foo()
      }
    }
  )
)

child <- Child$new()
child$foo()  # This will work
```

The key issue is that R6 doesn't handle well when you mix static and dynamic method definitions for the same method name. Choose one approach and stick with it consistently.

